  "editorial": {
    "title": "Detecting Cycle Length in Linked Lists",
    "intuition": "The problem of finding the length of a loop in a linked list can be approached by first detecting whether a cycle exists. A brute force method would involve traversing the list and checking every node against every other node, which is inefficient. A more intuitive approach involves using two pointers moving at different speeds to detect the cycle, leveraging the fact that they will eventually meet if a cycle exists.",
    "bruteForce": "The brute force approach to solving this problem involves checking every node against every other node to see if any node points back to a previous node, indicating a cycle. This method is highly inefficient due to its quadratic time complexity, making it impractical for large lists.",
    "betterSolution": "An improvement over the brute force method is to use a hash set to store the nodes as we traverse the list. If we encounter a node that is already in the set, we know a cycle exists. However, this approach still requires additional space proportional to the number of nodes.",
    "optimalSolution": "The optimal solution utilizes Floyd's Tortoise and Hare algorithm, also known as the slow and fast pointer technique. This method involves two pointers, one moving twice as fast as the other. If a cycle exists, these two pointers will eventually meet at some node within the cycle. After detecting the cycle, we can find the start of the cycle and then the length of the cycle by moving one pointer around the cycle while keeping the other pointer at the meeting point, counting the number of steps until they meet again.",
    "proofOfCorrectness": "The correctness of the optimal solution can be proven by understanding that if a cycle exists, the fast pointer will eventually catch up to the slow pointer within the cycle due to the difference in their speeds. Once the meeting point is found, resetting one pointer to the start and moving both at the same speed guarantees they will meet at the start of the cycle. Then, moving one pointer around the cycle while keeping the other at the start of the cycle allows us to count the length of the cycle accurately.",
